ounder and chief technical advisor for Alta Devices, a venture-backed company in Santa Clara, CA developing a transformational high efficiency/low cost photovoltaics technology, and Aonex Corporation, a compound semiconductor materials company.  He has also served an editorial board member for Surface Review and Letters.  Professor Atwater has actively served the materials community in various capacities, including [[Materials Research Society]] Meeting Chair (1997)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mrs.org/fall1997|title=1997 MRS Fall Meeting {{!}} Boston|website=www.mrs.org|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>, Materials Research Society President (2000)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mrs.org/past-mrs-presidents|title=Past MRS Presidents|website=www.mrs.org|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>, AVS Electronic Materials and Processing Division Chair (1999), and Board of Trustees of the Gordon Research Conferences.  In 2008, he served as Chair for the Gordon Research Conference on Plasmonics.\n\n==Research==\nHis research interests center around two interwoven research themes: [[photovoltaics]] and [[solar energy]]; and [[plasmon]]ics and optical [[metamaterials]].  Atwater and his group have been active in photovoltaics research for more than 20 years.  They have created new photovoltaic devices, including the silicon wire array solar cell, and layer-transferred fabrication approaches to III-V semiconductor III-V and [[Multijunction photovoltaic cell|multijunction cells]], as well as making advances in plasmonic light absorber structures for III-V compound and silicon thin films.  His research group\u2019s developments in the solar and plasmonics field have been featured in [[Scientific American]] and in research papers in [[Science (journal)|Science]], [[Nature Materials]], [[Nature Photonics]] and [[Advanced Materials]].\n\n== Awards ==\nAtwater is an MRS Fellow <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mrs.org/mrs-fellows-2011|title=2011 MRS Fellows|website=www.mrs.org|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>and has been honored by awards including the 2012 [[ENI award]] for Renewable and Non-Conventional Energy; MRS Kavli Lecturer in Nanoscience in 2010; Popular Mechanics Breakthrough Award, 2010; Joop Los Fellowship from the Dutch Society for Fundamental Research on Matter  in 2005,  A.T. & T. Foundation Award, 1990; NSF Presidential Young Investigator Award, 1989; IBM Faculty Development Award, 1989-1990; Member, Bohmische Physical Society, 1990; IBM Postdoctoral Fellowship, 1987. He is a member of the National Academy of Engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daedalus.caltech.edu/team-member/harry-atwater/|title=Professor Harry Atwater|website=Atwater Research Group|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> \n\n== Selected publications ==\n* {{cite journal|last1=Atwater|first1=Harry A.|last2=Polman|first2=Albert|title=Plasmonics for improved photovoltaic devices|journal=Nature Materials|volume=9|issue=3|year=2010|pages=205\u2013213|issn=1476-1122|doi=10.1038/nmat2629|pmid=20168344|bibcode=2010NatMa...9..205A|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/01b5d3ac672a11474e3a703119a1f80134b5017e}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Atwater|first1=Harry A.|title=The Promise of Plasmonics|journal=Scientific American|volume=296|issue=4|year=2007|pages=56\u201362|issn=0036-8733|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0407-56|pmid=17479631|bibcode=2007SciAm.296d..56A}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Maier|first1=Stefan A.|last2=Kik|first2=Pieter G.|last3=Atwater|first3=Harry A.|last4=Meltzer|first4=Sheffer|last5=Harel|first5=Elad|last6=Koel|first6=Bruce E.|last7=Requicha|first7=Ari A.G.|title=Local detection of electromagnetic energy transport below the diffraction limit in metal nanoparticle plasmon waveguides|journal=Nature Materials|volume=2|issue=4|year=2003|pages=229\u2013232|issn=1476-1122|doi=10.1038/nmat852|pmid=12690394|bibcode=2003NatMa...2..229M}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Walters|first1=Robert J.|last2=Bourianoff|first2=George I.|last3=Atwater|first3=Harry A.|title=Field-effect elect